But the day is still young.  Perhaps CHANCE ENCOUNTERs await!

@Bob T. 

Today I Learned that BURSAR and the anatomical term bursa both come from the Latin for “purse.” Maybe that will help? (I’m assuming you’re never sure if the second vowel is an A or an E.)

I fell once and broke open a bursa in my elbow. It didn’t really hurt, but it was months before the swelling went away.

@Eric Hougland 

Yeah, I had something like that with my elbow as well.  I had been really struggling with some code, and apparently I was really bearing down on the arms of the chair, and part of my elbow hurt a bit and was swollen.

And it did take a long, long time for it to finally return to normal.

@CaptainQuahog 

I thought it was a peephole too, but what are we looking into or what is reflected? It almost looks like some land in the distance with a blue sky and clouds and a reflection in a lake. 

@Peter C

I have no idea either. Is it a peephole as suggested or is it a doorbell? Best guess, it's on a door.

@Paul - I am a stranger to most everything about sports, but after decades of exposure have formed the definite opinion that Manchester United are the New York Yankees of your part of the world: obnoxious people who buy their championships and who are despised universally except for by their own fans. Is that wrong? It really is what I’ve gleaned.

I will cheer for anybody but the NYY, says this Philadelphia boy…

Go Greyhounds!

